{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645244"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:14:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:14:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18098"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18098"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.92,0,0.04,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10812"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114537"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10812"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96538"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25171"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25175"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114537"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOxytocin plays a crucial role in lactation and breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism by which oxytocin enables milk ejection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stimulates contraction of myoepithelial cells surrounding mammary alveoli","Increases blood flow to breast tissue","Increases milk protein synthesis","Promotes glucose uptake by mammary tissue","Stimulates mammary gland development"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOxytocin causes milk ejection (let-down) by \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulating contraction of myoepithelial cells surrounding mammary alveoli\u003C/strong\u003E. When an infant suckles, sensory nerve endings in the nipple trigger a neuroendocrine reflex that causes oxytocin release from the posterior pituitary. The oxytocin then acts on myoepithelial cells to squeeze milk from the alveoli into the ducts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing milk protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is a function of prolactin, not oxytocin. \u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating mammary gland development\u003C/strong\u003E occurs under the influence of oestrogen, progesterone and prolactin during pregnancy. \u003Cstrong\u003EPromoting glucose uptake by mammary tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is regulated by insulin and other metabolic hormones. While oxytocin may have minor vascular effects, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing blood flow to breast tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is not its primary mechanism for milk ejection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile prolactin is responsible for milk production, oxytocin\u0027s role is specifically in milk ejection through its effects on myoepithelial cell contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oxytocin causes milk ejection by stimulating contraction of myoepithelial cells in mammary glands.","Oxytocin is released in response to infant suckling via a neuroendocrine reflex.","Prolactin stimulates milk production, while oxytocin enables milk ejection."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 83; pg. 1058.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","i